    <h3 style="color: #FF0000; font-size: 1.75rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; text-align: center;">
      "The Enfant Terrible"
    </h3>
    
    <p style="font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 500; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; max-width: 800px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;">
      Wolfgang Weingart didn't set out to create a movement. He set out to teach students how to think differently.
    </p>
    
    <p style="font-size: 1.125rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; max-width: 800px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;">
      Born in Germany in 1941, Weingart learned the strict rules of Swiss typography at Basel School of Design. But he believed something crucial: <strong>"The only way to break typographic rules is to know them."</strong>
    </p>
    
    <div style="background: #FFFF00; padding: 1.5rem; border: 2px solid #000; margin: 2rem auto; max-width: 800px;">
      <p style="font-size: 1.5rem; font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; font-style: italic;">
        "I took Swiss typography as my starting point, but then I blew it apart."
      </p>
      <p style="font-weight: 700; margin: 0;">— Wolfgang Weingart</p>
    </div>
    
    <h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; font-size: 1.5rem; text-align: center;">His Revolutionary Techniques:</h4>
    
    <ul style="list-style-type: square; padding-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 1.125rem; line-height: 1.8; max-width: 800px; margin: 0 auto;">
      <li><strong>Letter spacing experiments</strong> - Testing limits of readability</li>
      <li><strong>Mixed typefaces and weights</strong> - Even within single words</li>
      <li><strong>Diagonal and rotated type</strong> - Breaking horizontal tyranny</li>
      <li><strong>Transparent film collages</strong> - Layering and texture</li>
      <li><strong>Trust intuition</strong> - As much as analytical skill</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
